## Memory Leaks

A memory leak is a programming error that causes a program to consume more and more memory over time, without releasing the memory that it has already allocated.

A memory leak can be caused by a programming error, such as forgetting to free a memory allocation, or by a failure to release a memory allocation when it is no longer needed.

Memory leaks can be difficult to detect and fix, because they can occur at any time, and they can be difficult to reproduce.

## Memory Leak Example

The following code is an example of a memory leak:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    // get buffer size from argv
    int buffer_size = atoi(argv[1]);
    // allocate buffer
    char *buffer = (char *)malloc(buffer_size);
    // do something with buffer
    //...
    // free buffer
    free(buffer);
}
```

The above code will allocate a buffer of size `buffer_size` bytes. The buffer is then freed using `free()`.

However, if the program exits before the buffer is freed, the memory will not be released.

## Memory Leak Detection

Memory leaks can be detected using a memory leak detector.

A memory leak detector is a program that periodically checks for memory leaks in a program.

Memory leak detectors can be difficult to write, because they must periodically check for memory leaks, which can be slow and expensive.

